#Text=Michał Falkener
#Text=Michael Falkener , [ 1 ]

#Text=Michał z Wrocławia , Michał Wrocławczyk , Michael de Wratislava , Michael Vratislaviensis ( ca. 1450 or 1460 in Wrocław – 1534 ) was a Polish [ 2 ] Scholastic philosopher , astronomer , astrologer , mathematician , theologian , philologist , and professor of the Kraków Academy . [ 3 ]
#Text=Life
#Text=Michał Falkener was born in Silesia to a family of wealthy burghers .

#Text=In Latin — the language favored by medieval European scholars , and used in his works — he is sometimes referred to as " Vratislaviensis " [ 4 ] or " Wratislaviensis " ( " the Wrocławian " ) in addition to " Michaelis de Vratislauia " [ 5 ] ( " Michael of Wrocław " ) .
#Text=In Polish he is , respectively , " Wrocławczyk " and " Michał z Wrocławia " ( " Michael of Wrocław " ) .

column1: #Text=In German , the place identifier is " of Breslau " [ 6 ] — " von Breslau " [ 7 ] or " aus Breslau . " [ 8 ]
#Text=Falkener entered the arts faculty of the Kraków Academy in 1478 , earning his bachelor 's in 1481 and defending his master 's thesis in 1488 .
#Text=Later he lectured there on astronomy , astrology , mathematics , physics , logic , grammar , and rhetoric , as well as scholastic and Aristotlian philosophy .
#Text=His students included Nicolaus Copernicus .
#Text=In 1495 he entered the Collegium Minus , and in 1501 the Collegium Maius .
#Text=In 1512 he joined the theological faculty , where he earned a doctorate in 1517 .
#Text=He twice ( 1499 and 1504 ) served as rector of the faculty of arts .
#Text=For several years he headed the Bursa Niemiecka , succeeding John of Głogów .
#Text=Falkener was a Thomist but an incomplete one since , in addition to Peripatetic- Thomist proofs for the existence of God , he also accepted St. Anselm 's proofs . [ 3 ]

#Text=In addition to more medieval pursuits , Falkener was interested in humanism : he knew and taught on classical and humanist authors , appreciating their linguistic and artistic abilities in particular .
#Text=He published and edited important introductions to and commentaries on song collections and religious texts .
#Text=Falkener 's first printed astrological predictions were published for the years 1494 – 95 ; 1506 saw the first edition of his Introductorium astronomiae Cracoviensis elucidans almanach .
#Text=He bequeathed his personal library to the Kraków Academy .
